The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Friday, April 09, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																																																		Indian Airlines has introduced specific flight fares between Calcutta and Chennai on flight CD 7265/7266 from Thursday. Passengers travelling to Chennai on the flight will have to pay Rs 6,500 instead of the normal sector fare of Rs 8,450, an IA spokesperson informed. This fare will only be available to passengers travelling on flights CD 7265/7266 and completing the travel on or before June 30, 2004. The flight has been introduced in the summer schedule which came into effect from March 28, 2004.																																																		The Asian Development Bank (ADB)-funded sewerage and drainage infrastructure project for the added areas of Behala, Garden Reach and Jadavpur will be flagged off in May as the ADB has disbursed Rs 45 lakh as part of its total loan package of Rs 1,800 crore on Calcuttas Environment Improvement project. An ADB delegation from Delhi met Mayor Subrata Mukherjee on Thursday.																																																		Bangla Sangeet Mela, a music festival, will be held in the city from April 14 to 21. Organised by the state information and culture and youth services, it will be held at five venues, youth services department secretary Jaya Dasgupta said on Thursday. Well-known and new talents  425 in all  will perform at the fair. The new voices are being selected through a competition. Singer Ramkumar Chattopadhyay would be felicitated at the festival.																																																		Calcutta High Court on Thursday adjourned the hearing of a contempt case against Biman Bose, Left Front chairman and CPM politburo member, till next week. Bose is facing contempt of court for criticising an order of Justice Amitava Lala restricting rallies on city roads on working days. 																																																		An unidentified body was recovered from platform number nine of Howrah station on Thursday. The body, with its head severed, was inside two bags. A murder case has been lodged. TO Happy Club and Health Point Nursing Home for setting up a free health check-up camp on the latters premises
